n, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Jean","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Like   Jane   and   Joan  , a medieval variant of Old French <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Towards the end of the Middle Ages this form became largely confined to Scotland. In the 20th century it became more widely used in the English-speaking world and enjoyed a period of great popularity, but it is now out of fashion. Among numerous well-known and influential bearers are the British novelists  Jean Plaidy  (  Eleanor Hibbert ,  1910–93 ) and  Jean Rhys  (  Ella Gwendolen Rees Williams ,  1894–1979 ), British actress  Jean Simmons  (  1929–2010 ), and American-born actress  Jean Seberg  (  1938–79 ). It is also found as a variant spelling of the masculine name   Gene ."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]},{"name":"Jeane","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jean ."]}]},{"name":"IV","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Form of   Yves   used in Germany and occasionally in the English-speaking world. It represents the nominative case of the Latinized form of the name."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Jean IV de Montoire Comte de Vendôme was born about 1175, in Vendôme, Loir-et-Cher, France, his father, Pierre de Montoire II, was 31 and his mother, Agnes Preuilly de Vendôme, was 26. He married Marguerite Eglantine de Palluau about 1205. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 3 daughters. In 1218, at the age of 44, his occupation is listed as seigneur. He died in 1240, in his hometown, at the ag